0.body: Geo Engine is a cloud-ready geo-spatial data processing platform. This documentation presents the foundations of the system and how to use it.

1.body: This chapter introduces the datatypes of Geo Engine.
1.title: Datatypes

11.body: This chapter introduces the operators of Geo Engine.
11.title: Operators

12.body: The BoxPlot is a plot operator that computes a box plot over a selection of numerical columns of a single vector dataset, or multiple raster datasets. Thereby, the operator considers all data in the given query rectangle. The boxes of the plot span the 1st and 3rd quartile and highlight the median. The whiskers indicate the minimum and maximum values of the corresponding attribute or raster.
12.title: BoxPlot

13.body: In case of vector data, the operator generates one box for each of the selected numerical attributes. The operator returns an error if one the selected attributes is not numeric.
13.title: Vector Data

14.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value columnNames Vec<String> The names of the attributes to generate boxes for. ["x","y"]
14.title: Parameter

15.body: For raster data, the operator generates one box for each input raster.
15.title: Raster Data

16.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value columnNames Vec<String> Optional : An alias for each input source. The operator will automatically name the boxes Raster-1, Raster-2, ... if this parameter is empty. If aliases are given, the number of aliases must match the number of input rasters. Otherwise an error is returned. ["A","B"]. includeNoData bool Flag whether to include no data values. true
16.title: Parameter

17.body: The operator consumes exactly one vector or multiple raster operators. Parameter Type source MultipleRasterOrSingleVectorSource
17.title: Inputs

18.body: The operator returns an error in the following cases. Vector data: The attribute for one of the given columnNames is not numeric. Vector data: The attribute for one of the given columnNames does not exist. Raster data: The length of the columnNames parameter does not match the number of input rasters.
18.title: Errors

19.body: If your dataset contains infinite or NAN values, they are ignored for the computation. Moreover, if your dataset contains more than 10.000values (which is likely for rasters), the median and quartiles are estimated using the P^2 algorithm described in: R. Jain and I. Chlamtac, The P^2 algorithm for dynamic calculation of quantiles and histograms without storing observations, Communications of the ACM, Volume 28 (October), Number 10, 1985, p. 1076-1085. https://www.cse.wustl.edu/~jain/papers/ftp/psqr.pdf
19.title: Notes

2.body: Measurements describe stored data, i.e. what is measured and in which unit.
2.title: Measurement

23.body: The Expression operator performs a pixel-wise mathematical expression on one or more raster sources. The expression is specified as a user-defined script in a very simple language. The output is a raster time series with the result of the expression and with time intervals that are the same as for the inputs. Users can specify an output data type. Internally, the expression is evaluated using floating-point numbers. An example usage scenario is to calculate NDVI for a red and a near-infrared raster channel. The expression uses two raster sources, referred to as A and B, and calculates the formula (A - B) / (A + B). When the temporal resolution is months, our output NDVI will also be a monthly time series.
23.title: Raster Expression

24.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value expression Expression Expression script (A - B) / (A + B) outputType RasterDataType A raster data type for the output U8 outputNoDataValue Number NO DATA value for the output -2 outputMeasurement Measurement Description about the output { "type": "continuous", "measurement": "NDVI"} mapNoData Boolean Should NO DATA values be mapped with the expression? Otherwise, they are mapped automatically to NO DATA. false
24.title: Parameters

25.body: The following describes the types used in the parameters.
25.title: Types

26.title: Expression

27.body: The Expression operator expects one to eight raster inputs. Parameter Type A SingleRasterSource B SingleRasterSource C SingleRasterSource … SingleRasterSource
27.title: Inputs

30.body: The GdalSource is a source operator that reads raster data using GDAL. The counter part for vector data is the OgrSource (TODO: link).
30.title: GdalSource

31.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value Default Value dataset DatasetId The id of the dataset to be loaded { "type": "internal", "datasetId": "a626c880-1c41-489b-9e19-9596d129859c"}
31.title: Parameters

33.body: If the given dataset does not exist or is not readable, an error is thrown.
33.title: Errors

35.body: The Reprojection operator reprojects data from one spatial reference system to another. It accepts exactly one input which can either be a raster or a vector data stream. The operator produces all data that, after reprojection, is contained in the query rectangle.
35.title: Reprojection

36.body: The concrete behavior depends on the data type.
36.title: Data type specifics

37.body: The reprojection operator reprojects all coordinates of the features individually. The result contains all features that, after reprojection, are intersected by the query rectangle. If not all coordinates of the vector data stream could be projected, the operator returns an error.
37.title: Vector data

38.body: To creates tiles in the target projection, the operator first loads the corresponding tiles in the source projection. Note, that in order to create one reprojected output tile, it may be necessary to load multiple source tiles. For each output pixel, the operator takes the value of the input pixel nearest to its upper left corner. In order to obtain precise results but avoid loading too much data, the operators estimates the resolution in which it loads the input raster stream. The estimate is based on the target resolution defined by the query rectangle and the relationship between the length of the diagonal of the query rectangle in both projections. Please refer to the source code for details. In case a tile, or part of a tile, is not available in the source projection because it is outside of the defined extent, the operator will produce pixels with no data values. If the input raster stream has no no data value defined, the value 0 will be used instead.
38.title: Raster data

39.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value targetSpatialReference String The srs string ( authority:code ) of the target spatial reference. EPSG:4326
39.title: Parameters

40.body: The Reprojection operator expects exactly one raster or vector input. Parameter Type source RasterOrVectorOperator
40.title: Inputs

41.body: The operator returns an error if the target projection is unknown or if the input data cannot be reprojected.
41.title: Errors

43.body: The ScatterPlot is a plot operator that computes a scatter plot over two attributes of a vector dataset. Thereby, the operator considers all data in the given query rectangle. In case of more than 500 points to plot, the representation changes from a regular scatter plot to a 2D Histogram with buckets determined from the underlying data.
43.title: ScatterPlot

44.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value columnX String The name of the attribute making up the x-axis of the plot. "width" columnY String The name of the attribute making up the y-axis of the plot. "height"
44.title: Parameter

45.body: The operator consumes exactly one vector operator. Parameter Type source SingleVectorSource
45.title: Inputs

46.body: The operator returns an error if one of the selected columns does not exist or is not numeric.
46.title: Errors

47.body: If your dataset contains infinite or NAN values, they are ignored for the computation. Moreover, if your dataset contains more than 10.000 values, the buckets of the histogram are generated based on those 10.000values. Later values outside those bounds are ignored.
47.title: Notes

49.body: The TemporalRasterAggregation aggregates a raster time series into uniform time intervals. The output is a time series that begins at the start of the query time. Each time slice has the same length, defined by the window parameter. The pixel values are computed by aggregating all rasters contained in the input that are valid in the current window using the defined aggregation method. All output slices that are contained in the query time interval are produced by the operator. An example usage scenario is to transform a daily raster time series into monthly aggregates. Here, the query should start at the beginning of the month and the window should be 1 month. The aggregation method allows calculating, e.g., the maximum or mean value for each pixel. If we perform a query with time [2021-01-01, 2021-04-1), we would get a time series with three time steps. If we perform a query with an instant like [2021-01-01, 2021-01-1), we will get a single time step containing the aggregated values for January 2021.
49.title: TemporalRasterAggregation

5.body: A contiuous variable that is measured in a certain unit.
5.title: Continuous

50.body: Parameter Type Description Example Value aggregation Aggregation method for aggregating pixels { "type": "max", "ignoreNoData": false} window TimeStep length of time steps { "granularity": "Months", "step": 1}
50.title: Parameters

51.body: The following describes the types used in the parameters.
51.title: Types

52.body: There are different methods that can be used to aggregate the raster time series. Encountering a no data value makes the aggregation value of a pixel also no data , unless the ignoreNoData parameter is set to true. Variant Parameters Description min ignoreNoData: bool minimum value max ignoreNoData: bool maximum value first ignoreNoData: bool first encountered value last ignoreNoData: bool last encountered value mean ignoreNoData: bool mean value
52.title: Aggregation

53.body: The length of the time intervals that are produced by the TemporalRasterAggregation operator are defined by the TimeStep type. Parameter Type Description Example Value granularity TimeGranularity granularity of the time steps Months step i32 number of time steps 1
53.title: TimeStep

54.body: The granularity of the time steps can take one of the following values. Variant Description Millis milliseconds Seconds seconds Minutes minutes Hours hours Days days Months months Years years
54.title: TimeGranularity

55.body: The TemporalRasterAggregation operator expects exactly one raster input. Parameter Type raster SingleRasterSource
55.title: Inputs

56.body: If the aggregation method is first, last or mean and the input raster has no no data value, an error is thrown.
56.title: Errors
